# **VS Code on host vs Container** {#vs-code-on-host-vs-container}

It's a mix of both. VS Code cleverly splits your configuration between your main OS and each container, giving you both global consistency and per-project customization.

Think of your setup like a toolbox:

* **User Settings (On Your OS):** This is your main **toolbox**. It defines the look and feel you prefer for every project, like the brand of your hammer or the color of the toolbox itself.  
* **Workspace Settings (In the Container):** This is a special **organizer tray** you put inside the toolbox for a specific job. It contains the special screws and drill bits needed only for that project. These settings override your global ones when you're working on that project.

## **On Your Main OS: Global User Settings** {#on-your-main-os:-global-user-settings}

These settings are tied to your VS Code installation and apply to every window you open, whether it's a local file or a container. This is where you configure your personal preferences that don't change from project to project.

**What lives here:**

* **Appearance:** Your theme, icon pack, font size, and window layout.  
* **Keybindings:** Your custom keyboard shortcuts.  
* **Editor Behavior:** General settings like autosave, word wrap, and cursor style.

You can find and edit these settings via the command palette (`Ctrl+Shift+P`) with **"Preferences: Open User Settings (JSON)"**.

## **Inside Each Container: Workspace Settings** {#inside-each-container:-workspace-settings}

These settings are project-specific and live inside your project's folder. When you open that project in a container, these settings are applied. This is the key to creating reproducible development environments because these settings can be committed to Git, ensuring everyone who works on the project gets the exact same editor configuration.

**What lives here:**

* **Language-Specific Paths:** The path to the Python interpreter inside the container (e.g., `/usr/local/bin/python`).  
* **Linters & Formatters:** Rules for tools like `black`, `ruff`, or `prettier`.  
* **Debugging Configurations:** The contents of your `launch.json` file.  
* **Project-Specific Extensions:** As we discussed, these are defined in your `devcontainer.json` file and are installed only inside the container.

These are typically stored in a `.vscode/settings.json` file within your project directory.

## **Venv vs. Dev Container \- Adapt Cloned Repo** {#venv-vs.-dev-container---adapt-cloned-repo}

* A **`venv`** is like a dedicated **bookshelf** for your project. It keeps your project's books (Python packages) separate from the books of other projects, but they all still exist in the same room (your main operating system).  
* A **Dev Container** is like a completely separate, fully-furnished **room** built just for your project. This room has its own air, its own specific desk (OS version), and its own dedicated bookshelf (Python and its packages). Nothing from outside the room can interfere with it.

### **Here‚Äôs a breakdown of what that means in practice:** {#here‚Äôs-a-breakdown-of-what-that-means-in-practice:}

| Feature | Virtual Environment (venv) | Dev Container (Docker) |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Isolation Scope** | Only isolates Python packages. | Isolates the entire stack: OS, system tools (like `git`), Python interpreter, packages, and even services like a database. |
| **System Tools** | Uses your main OS's tools. If a project needs a specific version of a tool like `ffmpeg`, you must install it on your host machine. | All tools are defined and installed **inside the container**. Your host machine can be completely clean. |
| **Python Version** | Is limited to the Python version you used to create it. Managing multiple Python versions on one host can be tricky. | The `Dockerfile` specifies the exact Python version (e.g., 3.9.7). You can work on one project using Python 3.9 and another using 3.12 without any conflicts. |
| **Reproducibility** | Good, but not perfect. A `requirements.txt` file doesn't account for system-level dependencies, which can cause the "it works on my machine" problem. | Perfect. The `Dockerfile` and `devcontainer.json` define the *entire* environment from scratch, ensuring it works identically for everyone, everywhere. |

## **VS Code Global vs Container**

### **Extensions Run Inside the Container** {#extensions-run-inside-the-container}

For a code assistant like Claude or GitHub Copilot to be truly useful, it needs to understand your project's complete context. This means it needs access to:

* All the code files in your project.  
* The specific version of Python you're using.  
* The libraries and frameworks listed in your `requirements.txt`.

All of this information exists **inside the container**. Therefore, the core of the extension must also run inside the container to be able to see and analyze it. If it ran globally, it would be blind to the specific environment of each project.

### **What Stays Global (The Magic Part) üîë** {#what-stays-global-(the-magic-part)-üîë}

While the extension's engine runs in the container, VS Code handles the user-facing parts globally to make your life easy:

* **Authentication:** When you log in to your Anthropic or GitHub account, VS Code securely stores that credential on your main OS (at the User/Global level).  
* **Seamless Experience:** When a new Dev Container starts and installs the Claude extension, the extension automatically gets the login token from the global VS Code application. **You do not have to log in again.**

This is why it *feels* global. You log in once, and every container you create from then on will have a fully authenticated and ready-to-use code assistant.

Of course. You can easily incorporate Excalidraw into your VS Code workflow, and there are a couple of great ways to do it depending on your needs.

The easiest method is using the official VS Code extension, which works perfectly within your Dev Container setup.

## **Opening a Docker Container** {#opening-a-docker-container}

How you open a doc

Both these methods get you to the same end result: your code running inside a fully configured Dev Container. The choice between them often comes down to personal preference and your specific needs.

| Feature | Workflow A: Clone Locally, then "Reopen" | Workflow B: "Clone in Container Volume" |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Code Location** | Directly in a folder on your host machine (e.g., `~/Projects/my-repo`). | Managed by Docker in a dedicated volume. |
| **File Access** | Easy to access and edit files from your host's file explorer or other tools outside of VS Code. | Files are "inside" Docker. You primarily interact with them through VS Code. |
| **Performance** | Can be slow if you have a huge number of files, especially on Windows or macOS due to filesystem translation. | **Generally faster**, as Docker's internal volume management is highly optimized. |
| **Host System** | The cloned repo folder exists on your main filesystem. | Keeps your host filesystem **perfectly clean**. There are no project files outside of Docker's control. |

# **Terminals and Containers**

Yes, this is a very common point of confusion. The key is to have a clear mental model for what each terminal can "see" and "do."

Here‚Äôs the simplest rule: Use the **Host Terminal** to build and manage your containers (the "template"). Use the **Container Terminal** to run code and work with the tools inside the running environment.

## **The "Car and Driver" Mental Model**

Think of your container as a car and your host machine as the world outside.

* **Host Terminal (Outside the Car):** When you're in a terminal on your main OS, you are **standing outside the car**. From here, you can build the car (docker build), start the engine (docker-compose up), open the doors, or look under the hood. You can't drive the car from the outside.  
* **Container Terminal (Inside the Car):** When you are in the terminal inside your Dev Container, you are **sitting in the driver's seat**. From here, you can drive the car (python app.py), use the radio (ruff check .), or see what's in the glove box (ls \-l). You can't rebuild the car's engine while you're driving it.

## **Guidelines for Navigating Terminals**

Here are the specific use-cases and the correct terminal for each.

#### **Scenario 1: Building, Fixing, or Managing the Container ("Template")**

* **Your Goal:** The container isn't building correctly, or you need to start/stop the services. You are editing files like Dockerfile, docker-compose.yml, or .env.  
* **‚úÖ Which Terminal?** Your **Host Terminal** (e.g., your main Ubuntu/Powershell terminal) OR the VS Code Integrated Terminal **before** you have connected to the container.  
* **üìç Where?** In the **root directory of your project** on your host machine‚Äîthe same folder that contains your Dockerfile or docker-compose.yml.  
* **Why?** The docker and docker-compose commands are installed on your host OS. They are the tools you use to build the "car." They need to be run from the project's directory to find the blueprints.  
* **Common Commands:**  
  Bash  
  docker-compose up \--build  
  docker build \-t my-app .  
  docker ps

---

#### **\#\# Scenario 2: Working with Your Application and Code**

* **Your Goal:** You want to run your Python script, install a temporary package, run tests, or use tools like git or ruff that are part of your defined environment.  
* **‚úÖ Which Terminal?** The **VS Code Integrated Terminal** *after* you have used **"Reopen in Container."** The bottom-left corner of VS Code will be green and show your container's name.  
* **üìç Where?** You will automatically be placed in the correct project directory (/workspace or /app) **inside the container**.  
* **Why?** This terminal is running inside the "car." It has access to the correct Python version, all the packages from your requirements.txt, and the specific tools you installed in your Dockerfile. Your host machine likely doesn't have this specific setup.  
* **Common Commands:**  
  Bash  
  python main.py  
  ruff check .  
  pip install "black\[jupyter\]"

### **Quick Reference Table**

| Your Goal | Which Terminal to Use? | Where to Be? (Directory) | Analogy |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Build, run, fix, or manage containers** | **Host Terminal** | Project Root (on Host) | **Outside the car** (building it) |
| **Run app code, install packages, use tools** | **Container Terminal** | Workspace (in Container) | **Inside the car** (driving it) |

# **Multi-Container Docker** {#multi-container-docker}

## **Dockerfile vs. docker-compose.yml** {#dockerfile-vs.-docker-compose.yml}

A **`Dockerfile`** is a blueprint for building a *single* container image. A **`docker-compose.yml`** file is a script for defining and running a *multi-container application*.

Think of it like building a house:

* **`requirements.txt`**: This is your shopping list for the materials needed inside the house (e.g., specific Python packages).  
* **`Dockerfile`**: This is the **blueprint for the house itself**. It's a step-by-step guide on how to build one house, and it refers to your shopping list (`requirements.txt`) to know what materials to install.  
* **`docker-compose.yml`**: This is the **master plan for the entire property**. It says, "Build a house using the house blueprint here, build a separate garage over there, and build a guest cottage back here. Then, make sure they are all connected to the same network and can easily communicate."

---

### **`Dockerfile`: The Blueprint for One** {#dockerfile:-the-blueprint-for-one}

The `Dockerfile` contains the instructions to create a single image. Its job is to set up the environment *inside* that one image.

This is where `requirements.txt` is directly used. The `Dockerfile` has commands to copy the file into the image and then run `pip install` on it.

Dockerfile

\# Tells Docker how to build one image

Start from a base

FROM python:3.11-slim

Copy the "shopping list"

COPY requirements.txt .

Install everything on the list

RUN pip install \--no-cache-dir \-r requirements.txt

Copy the application code

COPY . .\`

---

### **`docker-compose.yml`: The Conductor for an Orchestra** {#docker-compose.yml:-the-conductor-for-an-orchestra}

More experienced developers work on applications that are rarely just a single service. A typical web application might need:

1. **The App:** The Python code itself (e.g., a FastAPI server).  
2. **A Database:** A separate service like PostgreSQL to store data.  
3. **A Cache:** A separate service like Redis for performance.

`docker-compose.yml` lets you define all these services in one file and manage them with a single command (`docker-compose up`). It orchestrates how these separate containers start, stop, and communicate with each other.

Here's how it uses the `Dockerfile`:

YAML

\`\# Tells Docker how to run a multi-container application services:

This is your main Python application

app: \# "Build the image for this service using the Dockerfile in the current directory" build: . ports: \- "8001:8001" \# This service depends on the database being ready depends\_on: \- db

This is a completely separate container for the database

db: image: postgres:15-alpine \# Use a pre-built image from Docker Hub environment: \- POSTGRES\_USER=myuser \- POSTGRES\_PASSWORD=mypassword\`

---

### **How This Works with Your Dev Container** {#how-this-works-with-your-dev-container}

Your Dev Container can intelligently use **either** file as its foundation.

* **If a project only has a `Dockerfile`**, your `devcontainer.json` points to it, as we've already done.  
* **If a project has a `docker-compose.yml`**, you tell your `devcontainer.json` to use that instead. This is incredibly powerful because it will not only launch your development environment but also all the other services (like the database) that your application needs to run.

Here‚Äôs how your `devcontainer.json` would look for a Compose project:

JSON

\`{ "name": "My Compose-Based Dev Environment",

// Point to your docker-compose.yml file "dockerComposeFile": "../docker-compose.yml",

// Tell VS Code which service to attach to for development "service": "app",

// The workspace folder inside the container "workspaceFolder": "/app",

"customizations": { "vscode": { "extensions": \["ms-python.python", "Anthropic.anthropic-vscode"\] } } }\`

When you "Reopen in Container," VS Code will run `docker-compose up` in the background, starting both your `app` and `db` containers. It will then attach your VS Code window to the `app` container, giving you a terminal and full access to your code, while the PostgreSQL database runs happily alongside it, ready for your app to connect.

## **Containers Connect via Virtual Networks** {#containers-connect-via-virtual-networks}

Docker "just knows" how to connect services, but it's more powerful than just connecting ports.

* **Ports (`ports: "8001:8001"`)** are primarily for exposing a container to the **outside world** (i.e., to your host machine's network, so you can access it from your browser).3  
* **Virtual Networks** are for communication **between containers**.

When you run `docker-compose up`, Docker creates a private virtual network and attaches all the defined services to it. On this private network, each service gets an internal DNS entry that matches its name.

This means your `app` container can find your `db` container by simply using the hostname `db`. The database port (`5432`) is just the specific "doorbell" to ring at that address.

Your application's database connection string would look like this:

postgresql://myuser:mypassword@db:5432/mydatabase

Docker's internal network automatically resolves the hostname `db` to the private IP address of the database container. It's seamless and requires no manual configuration.

## **Data Storage: Bind Mount** {#data-storage:-bind-mount}

This is a very common and smart practice, especially for large datasets like LLM models or databases. By default, Docker stores its named volumes in a system directory on your main drive. To use your separate data drive, you use a **bind mount**.1

A bind mount directly maps a specific folder from your host machine (your data drive) to a folder inside the container.2

Here‚Äôs how you would modify your `docker-compose.yml` for Ollama to store its models on a separate drive mounted at `/mnt/my_data_drive/`:

YAML

`services: ollama: image: ollama/ollama volumes: # This is a bind mount. # It maps the host folder to the folder where Ollama stores models inside the container. - /mnt/my_data_drive/ollama_models:/root/.ollama ports: - "11434:11434"`

Now, when Ollama downloads a model, it will be saved directly to your data drive, leaving your main OS drive untouched.

### **The "Same Drive" Myth** {#the-"same-drive"-myth}

Your guess that the service has to be on the same drive is a common misconception. In reality, the service (the container) and its data (the volume or bind mount) are completely decoupled.

Think of your computer as an office building. The container is a specific office. A named volume is a filing cabinet inside that office. A bind mount is a high-speed pneumatic tube that connects your office directly to a massive, secure file warehouse next door (your separate data drive).

The people working in the office don't care whether the files are in the local cabinet or the warehouse; they just know the address to request them. The physical location is irrelevant.

## **Example: Simple One Service ‚ÄúExcalidraw** {#example:-simple-one-service-‚Äúexcalidraw}

Below is an example of how one could add one service to a container \- either in the same dev container or as a separate service in its own.

### **Method 1: The Excalidraw VS Code Extension** {#method-1:-the-excalidraw-vs-code-extension}

This is the most direct and seamless way to add diagramming to your projects. It allows you to create and edit `.excalidraw` files right inside your VS Code editor, just like any other code file.

Since Excalidraw is primarily a visual tool, its extension runs on the **client-side** of VS Code. This means it integrates with the user interface you see on your host machine, while the files themselves are saved inside your container's project directory.

### **How to Set It Up:** {#how-to-set-it-up:}

1. **Connect to Your Container:** Make sure you've reopened your project in its Dev Container.  
2. **Install the Extension:** Open the Extensions sidebar (`Ctrl+Shift+X`), search for **"Excalidraw"**, and install the one by **Visual Studio Code**. VS Code will handle installing it correctly.  
3. **Create a Diagram:** Create a new file with an `.excalidraw` or `.excalidraw.svg` extension (e.g., `architecture.excalidraw.svg`). When you open this file, the Excalidraw canvas will appear directly in your editor tab.

Your diagrams are saved as files right alongside your code, making it simple to version control them with Git.

To automatically have it available in your projects, add its ID to your `devcontainer.json`:

JSON

`"customizations": { "vscode": { "extensions": [ "ms-python.python", "Anthropic.anthropic-vscode", "vscode-excalidraw.excalidraw-editor" // <-- Add Excalidraw here ] } }`

### **Method 2: Running Excalidraw as a Separate Docker Service** {#method-2:-running-excalidraw-as-a-separate-docker-service}

This method is useful if you want a standalone instance of Excalidraw that can be used for a number of purposes \- for example, a browser-based version of Excalidraw for collaboration. Here, you'll use a `docker-compose.yml` file to launch your main development container *and* a separate container running the Excalidraw web application.

### **How to Set It Up:** {#how-to-set-it-up:-1}

1. Create a `docker-compose.yml` file in your project's root directory.  
2. Define two services: one for your application (built from your `Dockerfile`) and one for Excalidraw using a pre-built image.

Here's an example `docker-compose.yml`:

YAML

\`services:

Your main development container

app: build: . volumes: \- .:/workspace:cached command: sleep infinity \# Keep the container running deploy: resources: reservations: devices: \- driver: nvidia count: all capabilities: \[gpu\]

The Excalidraw container

excalidraw: image: excalidraw/excalidraw:latest ports: \- "8080:80" \# Map host port 8080 to the container's port 80\`

1. Run `docker-compose up -d` in your terminal.  
2. You can now access your development environment through VS Code as usual, and your team can access a shared Excalidraw canvas by navigating to `http://localhost:8080` in their web browsers.

---

### **Which Method Should You Choose?** {#which-method-should-you-choose?}

Here‚Äôs a quick comparison to help you decide:

| Feature | VS Code Extension | Docker Service |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Best For** | Quick, personal diagrams; version controlling diagrams with code. | Team collaboration; a persistent, shared whiteboard. |
| **Setup** | Very simple (install extension). | More complex (requires `docker-compose.yml`). |
| **Access** | Inside VS Code only. | Any web browser on your network. |
| **File Storage** | Saved as `.excalidraw` files in your project folder. | Managed within the Excalidraw web app's own storage. |

## **Example: Persistent Database in Separate Container** {#example:-persistent-database-in-separate-container}

To have a single, persistent database that multiple, separate application containers can all connect to and use, you combine three core Docker concepts:

1. **Docker Compose:** To manage all the containers as a single unit.  
2. **Named Volumes:** To ensure the database's data persists even if the container is deleted.  
3. **Shared Networks:** To allow the app containers to easily find and talk to the database container.

### **The Key Components** {#the-key-components}

* **Named Volumes (The Persistent Hard Drive):** This is the solution to your persistence problem. A named volume is a dedicated piece of storage managed by Docker that lives outside any specific container. You can attach this volume to your database container. If you ever delete, recreate, or update the database container, the volume (and all your precious data) remains untouched and simply re-attaches to the new container.  
* **Docker Networks (The Private Network):** By default, all the services defined in a single `docker-compose.yml` file are joined to a private virtual network. This is crucial because it allows your application containers to find and connect to your database container by simply using its service name (e.g., `db`) as the hostname. You don't have to worry about IP addresses.

### **Code Example `docker-compose.yml`** {#code-example-docker-compose.yml}

Here is what a `docker-compose.yml` file would look like for this exact scenario. It defines one persistent database and two different web applications that both connect to it.

YAML

\`services:

The central, persistent database service

db: image: postgres:15-alpine restart: always environment: \- POSTGRES\_USER=myuser \- POSTGRES\_PASSWORD=mypassword volumes: \# This line is critical for persistence. \# It maps the "db-data" volume to the folder inside the container where PostgreSQL stores its data. \- db-data:/var/lib/postgresql/data

First application that uses the database

webapp1: build: ./webapp1\_folder \# Assumes this app has its own Dockerfile restart: always ports: \- "8001:8000" environment: \# This app connects to the database using the service name "db" \- DATABASE\_HOSTNAME=db

Second, completely different application that also uses the database

webapp2: build: ./webapp2\_folder \# Assumes this app also has its own Dockerfile restart: always ports: \- "8002:8000" environment: \- DATABASE\_HOSTNAME=db

This top-level key declares the named volume, ensuring Docker manages it.

volumes: db-data:\`

### **How It Works in Practice** {#how-it-works-in-practice}

1. You run `docker-compose up -d`.  
2. Docker creates the `db-data` volume, a private network, and starts the `db`, `webapp1`, and `webapp2` containers.  
3. Both `webapp1` and `webapp2` can connect to the database using the hostname `db`. Any data they write is stored in the `db-data` volume.  
4. Later, you can run `docker-compose down`. This stops and removes the containers. However, the `db-data` volume is **not deleted**.  
5. The next time you run `docker-compose up`, a new database container will be created and will re-attach to the existing `db-data` volume, starting up with all of its data perfectly intact.

## **Multi-Container Database \= Service-oriented Architecture** {#multi-container-database-=-service-oriented-architecture}

This is a classic **service-oriented architecture**. Your Supabase container acts as a centralized, persistent "data service," which is then consumed by multiple, independent applications (your AI agents and analytics tools). Docker Compose is the ideal tool to manage this.

[Image of a microservices architecture diagram](https://encrypted-tbn3.gstatic.com/licensed-image?q=tbn:ANd9GcQkLXz7d8D01cCHMSXtmNksKb2yOLtGdvUFEY41hiQXw_qZeY0LKffu0wFU_660v_aY22hKGrAY9QZRu__odkjg-2Gpc6b9JOazqi6eedbzaas6oxk)

![][image1]

---

### **How the Architecture Works**

Your docker-compose.yml file will be the master plan for this entire system. It will define each component as a separate, interconnected service.

1. **The Data Service (supabase):** This will be the core of your setup. It will be a PostgreSQL container (as Supabase uses Postgres) with its data stored safely in a **named volume**. This ensures that all your knowledgebase data‚Äîstructured tables, vector embeddings, and different data versions‚Äîis persistent and secure.  
2. **The AI Agent Consumers:** Each of your AI agents will be its own service, built from its own Dockerfile. Inside its environment configuration, you'll simply tell it how to find the database‚Äîby using the service name supabase.  
3. **The Analytics Consumers:** Similarly, any other application that needs to run SQL queries will be another service. It will connect to the very same supabase service to get the data it needs for analytics and structured outputs.

All of these services will run on a private Docker network, allowing them to communicate securely and efficiently.

### **Example docker-compose.yml**

Here is a simplified example of what this master plan might look like.

YAML

services:  
  \# 1\. The Central Data Service  
  supabase:  
    image: supabase/postgres:15  \# Use the official Supabase Postgres image  
    restart: always  
    volumes:  
      \# This named volume makes all your knowledgebase data persistent  
      \- supabase-data:/var/lib/postgresql/data  
    environment:  
      \- POSTGRES\_USER=myuser  
      \- POSTGRES\_PASSWORD=mypassword  
      \- POSTGRES\_DB=knowledgebase

  \# 2\. An AI Agent Consumer  
  rag-agent-alpha:  
    build: ./agents/alpha\_agent \# This agent has its own Dockerfile  
    restart: always  
    depends\_on:  
      \- supabase \# Tells Docker to start the database before the agent  
    environment:  
      \# The agent connects to the database using the service name "supabase"  
      \- DATABASE\_URL=postgresql://myuser:mypassword@supabase:5432/knowledgebase

  \# 3\. An Analytics App Consumer  
  analytics-dashboard:  
    build: ./apps/dashboard\_app \# This app has its own Dockerfile  
    restart: always  
    ports:  
      \- "8080:80" \# Expose the dashboard to your browser  
    depends\_on:  
      \- supabase  
    environment:  
      \- DATABASE\_URL=postgresql://myuser:mypassword@supabase:5432/knowledgebase

\# This declares the named volume to ensure Docker manages it  
volumes:  
  supabase-data:

### **Key Benefits of This Approach**

* **Decoupling:** Your agents and apps don't care *how* the database is run. You can update or restart the supabase service without affecting them.  
* **Centralized Data:** Your knowledgebase is the "single source of truth," managed in one place.  
* **Scalability:** You can easily add a new rag-agent-beta or a reporting-service to the docker-compose.yml file without touching the existing components.  
* **Reproducibility:** The entire multi-service application can be launched on any machine with Docker using a single command: docker-compose up.
